## Rendering guidance
- Weave the subject, style, composition, mood, and palette into one flowing
  description of the scene, as a director would describe a shot, rather than
  a bullet list of disconnected attributes.
- Be concrete: name materials, textures, and surface details instead of
  generic nouns (e.g. "weathered oak" rather than "wood").
- Where the composition implies a camera framing, use precise photographic
  terms (e.g. "low angle," "shallow depth of field," "wide shot") to make
  the framing unambiguous.
- Describe lighting explicitly (direction, quality, and mood) rather than
  leaving it to be inferred from "mood" alone.
- Honor every constraint by depicting the desired state directly, rather
  than only negating what to avoid.
